/td><td><p>33%</p></td><td><p>37%</p></td><td><p>44%</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Not Upheld</p></td><td><p>61%</p></td><td><p>74%</p></td><td><p>49%</p></td><td><p>41%</p></td><td><p>28%</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p>Average clearance times, for the last five years, in respect of resolution, settlement and full investigations by the Independent Case Examiner Office are detailed below.</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p>Average Cleared Times (weeks)</p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td></tr><tr><td><p> </p></td><td><p>Resolution</p></td><td><p>Settled</p></td><td><p>ICE Report</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2011/12</p></td><td><p>8</p></td><td><p>49</p></td><td><p>51</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2012/13</p></td><td><p>9</p></td><td><p>39</p></td><td><p>45</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2013/14</p></td><td><p>9</p></td><td><p>24</p></td><td><p>33</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2014/15</p></td><td><p>6</p></td><td><p>27</p></td><td><p>29</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2015/16</p></td><td><p>8</p></td><td><p>38</p></td><td><p>44</p></td></tr></tbody></table>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline Nokes","50577 ; 50580","2016-11-03T17:22:24.63Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622119/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622119/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622119/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-10-26","Independent Case Examiner","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how many cases have been dealt with by the Independent Case Examiner in each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for Neil Gray","Airdrie and Shotts","Neil Gray","50578"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622120","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-11-02","We welcomed the Cessation of Hostilities from 19-22 October. It is critical that all parties to the conflict renew their commitment to a Cessation of Hostilities for the sake of the people of Yemen. All parties must engage constructively with the De-escalation and Coordination Committee so that when incidents of concern are raised they can be addressed effectively to reduce the likelihood of escalation.","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood",,"2016-11-02T15:36:57.907Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622120/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622120/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622120/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-10-26","Yemen: Armed Conflict","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what assessment he has made of the observation and effectiveness of the recent ceasefire in Yemen.","false","Biography information for Mrs Flick Drummond","Portsmouth South","Mrs Flick Drummond","50377"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622121","HM Treasury","false","2016-10-31","<p>The UK remains a full member of the EU until we formally exit and all rights and obligations under the EU, including trade defence measures, still apply. We will continue to support the EU’s trade agenda and we look forward to the Commission’s proposals on Market Economy Status later in the Autumn.</p><p> </p>","Brighton, Kemptown","Simon Kirby",,"2016-10-31T16:41:03.127Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622121/answer","Biography information for Simon Kirby","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622121/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622121/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-10-26","Overseas Trade: China","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, whether the Government plans unilaterally to grant China market economy status in the event of the UK leaving the EU and its single market.","false","Biography information for Tom Blenkinsop","Middlesbrough South and East Cleveland","Tom Blenkinsop","50493"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622122","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2016-10-31","<p>The Department for Business Energy and Industrial Strategy does not hold this information.</p><p><strong> </strong></p>","Stourbridge","Margot James",,"2016-10-31T15:07:05.407Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622122/answer","Biography information for Margot James","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622122/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622122/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2016-10-26","Migrant Workers: Trade Unions","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what information his Department holds on the number of employers who have prevented migrant workers from joining a union during their time working in the UK.","false","Biography information for Tom Blenkinsop","Middlesbrough South and East Cleveland","Tom Blenkinsop","50494"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622123","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2016-10-31","<p>The Department for Business Energy and Industrial Strategy is not aware of any representations on migrant employees in the UK being forced to repay funds paid to them as a result of shortfalls in wages to their employers upon return to their country of origin.</p>","Stourbridge","Margot James",,"2016-10-31T15:10:05.55Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622123/answer","Biography information for Margot James","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622123/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622123/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2016-10-26","Migrant Workers: Pay","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, pursuant to the Answer of 20 October 2016 to Question 48990 and the correction to that Answer of 21 October 2016, whether he has received representations on migrant employees in the UK being forced to repay funds to their employers which had been paid to such employees as a result of shortfalls in wages upon return to their country of origin.","false","Biography information for Tom Blenkinsop","Middlesbrough South and East Cleveland","Tom Blenkinsop","50502"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622124","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-10-31","<p>We are investing £1.3 billion to reform and modernise the prison estate to make it more efficient, safer and focused on supporting prisoner rehabilitation. We will build new prisons and close prisons that are in poor condition and those which do not have a long-term future in the estate.</p><p>We are currently considering sites for new prison places and will set out plans shortly.</p>","East Surrey","Mr Sam Gyimah",,"2016-10-31T17:22:47.837Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622124/answer","Biography information for Mr Sam Gyimah","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622124/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622124/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-10-26","Prisons: Capital Investment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, when she plans to announce the sites for the Prisons Investment programme.","false","Biography information for Mr Peter Bone","Wellingborough","Mr Peter Bone","50365"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622125","HM Treasury","false","2016-11-03","<p>Tax credits recipients are entitled to submit a request for Mandatory Reconsideration if a decision made by Concentrix is thought to be incorrect. Often, claimants are required to submit information that had originally been requested as part of a Mandatory Reconsideration.</p><p> </p><p>In addition, the performance of Concentrix is monitored by HM Revenue and Customs (HMRC). Any errors in tax credit awards checked by HMRC, including those where no Mandatory Reconsideration request has been submitted, are both reinstated and backdated, and so there are no savings to the Exchequer associated with these cases.</p><p> </p><p>HMRC does not have a comprehensive set of information on cases where no mandatory reconsideration has been submitted.</p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison","50316","2016-11-03T17:26:37.637Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622125/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622125/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622125/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-10-26","Concentrix","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what estimate his Department has made of how much of the tax credit savings to date were a result of erroneous decisions made by Concentrix against legitimate tax credit recipients.","false","Biography information for Justin Madders","Ellesmere Port and Neston","Justin Madders","50476"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622126","HM Treasury","false","2016-11-03","<p>HM Revenue and Customs (HMRC) is urgently focusing on resolving the outstanding Concentrix cases.</p><p> </p><p>If people feel they have had their tax credits incorrectly withdrawn, they should urgently contact HMRC. HMRC will review all complaint cases and pay redress where appropriate. This will be carried out on a customer by customer basis.</p><p> </p><p>Any errors in tax credit awards checked by HMRC, including those where no Mandatory Reconsideration request has been submitted, are both reinstated and backdated.</p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison","50310","2016-11-03T14:49:16.083Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622126/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622126/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622126/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-10-26","Concentrix","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what timescale has been set for incorrect tax credit withdrawals by Concentrix to be remedied; and what plans he has to compensate clamants for any missing time periods.","false","Biography information for Justin Madders","Ellesmere Port and Neston","Justin Madders","50477"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622127","HM Treasury","false","2016-11-03","<p>HM Revenue and Customs (HMRC) uses a wide range of mechanisms to monitor the performance of Concentrix. This includes active supplier management via dedicated commercial and operational teams and against defined targets, regular service delivery reviews and the collation of defined performance management information against targets.</p><p>As such, meetings (including telephone conferences) are conducted on a daily, weekly, monthly, quarterly and annual basis. HM Treasury also monitors the performance of Concentrix in conjunction with HMRC. Given these circumstances specific dates of meetings are not collated and published.</p><p>HMRC and HM Treasury do not routinely publish details of discussions with external suppliers.</p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison","50307 ; 50308 ; 50309 ; 50479 ; 50480","2016-11-03T17:38:03.277Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622127/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622127/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622127/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-10-26","Concentrix: Standards","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, if he will publish any performance reviews of the Concentrix tax credit contract conducted by (a) HM Revenue and Customs and (b) his Department.","false","Biography information for Justin Madders","Ellesmere Port and Neston","Justin Madders","50478"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622128","HM Treasury","false","2016-11-03","<p>HM Revenue and Customs (HMRC) uses a wide range of mechanisms to monitor the performance of Concentrix. This includes active supplier management via dedicated commercial and operational teams and against defined targets, regular service delivery reviews and the collation of defined performance management information against targets.</p><p>As such, meetings (including telephone conferences) are conducted on a daily, weekly, monthly, quarterly and annual basis. HM Treasury also monitors the performance of Concentrix in conjunction with HMRC. Given these circumstances specific dates of meetings are not collated and published.</p><p>HMRC and HM Treasury do not routinely publish details of discussions with external suppliers.</p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison","50307 ; 50308 ; 50309 ; 50478 ; 50480","2016-11-03T17:38:02.967Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622128/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622128/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622128/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-10-26","Concentrix: Standards","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, if he will publish the dates of any meeting which were held between Concentrix and (a) HM Revenue and Customs and (b) his Department for the purposes of monitoring the performance of Concentrix.","false","Biography information for Justin Madders","Ellesmere Port and Neston","Justin Madders","50479"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622129","HM Treasury","false","2016-11-03","<p>As announced on 7th October, the National Audit Office will be conducting an investigation into HM Revenue and Customs’ contract with Concentrix.</p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison",,"2016-11-03T14:58:58.033Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622129/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622129/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622129/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-10-26","Concentrix: Standards","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, if he will conduct an official investigation into HM Revenue and Customs' conduct in relation to monitoring the performance of Concentrix since that company was awarded the tax credit contract in 2014.","false","Biography information for Justin Madders","Ellesmere Port and Neston","Justin Madders","50505"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622130","HM Treasury","false","2016-11-03","<p>HM Revenue and Customs (HMRC) uses a wide range of mechanisms to monitor the performance of Concentrix. This includes active supplier management via dedicated commercial and operational teams and against defined targets, regular service delivery reviews and the collation of defined performance management information against targets.</p><p>As such, meetings (including telephone conferences) are conducted on a daily, weekly, monthly, quarterly and annual basis. HM Treasury also monitors the performance of Concentrix in conjunction with HMRC. Given these circumstances specific dates of meetings are not collated and published.</p><p>HMRC and HM Treasury do not routinely publish details of discussions with external suppliers.</p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison","50307 ; 50308 ; 50309 ; 50478 ; 50479","2016-11-03T17:38:03.34Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622130/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622130/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622130/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-10-26","Concentrix: Standards","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, if he will publish the minutes of any meeting which were held between Concentrix and (a) HM Revenue and Customs and (b) his Department for the purposes of monitoring the performance of Concentrix.","false","Biography information for Justin Madders","Ellesmere Port and Neston","Justin Madders","50480"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622131","HM Treasury","false","2016-11-03","<p>People with outstanding tax credit claims should contact HM Revenue and Customs (HMRC).</p><p> </p><p>The Concentrix contract is managed by the HMRC Commercial Team supported by HMRC Operational Service Management Team.</p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison","50475","2016-11-03T15:13:06.57Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622131/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622131/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622131/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-10-26","Concentrix: Standards","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, who (a) in his Department and (b) at HM Revenue and Customs has the responsibility for monitoring the Concentrix tax credit contract.","false","Biography information for Justin Madders","Ellesmere Port and Neston","Justin Madders","50481"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622132","HM Treasury","false","2016-11-03","<p>In March 2016 HMRC reached an agreement with two of its major suppliers, Capgemini and Fujitsu on a phased exit from its Aspire contract.</p><p>No HM Revenue and Customs staff based at Cumbernauld were placed into the redeployment pool as a result of this agreement.</p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison",,"2016-11-03T17:34:07.997Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622132/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622132/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622132/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-10-26","Revenue and Customs: Cumbernauld","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, how many HM Revenue and Customs (HMRC) staff at Cumbernauld Tax Office have been placed in the redeployment pool as a result of HMRC's decision to end its contract with Fujitsu early on that side.","false","Biography information for Justin Madders","Ellesmere Port and Neston","Justin Madders","50482"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622133","HM Treasury","false","2016-11-03","<p>HM Revenue and Customs and Synnex-Concentrix UK Limited are in discussions to achieve a managed early exit from the contract. There are commercial sensitivities around the details at this time.</p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison","50312","2016-11-03T15:19:40.403Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622133/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622133/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622133/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-10-26","Concentrix","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, whether he plans to seek compensation from Concentrix to cover the cost of HM Revenue and Customs' staff resolving tax credit claims (a) to date and (b) for the remaining duration of the contract with Concentrix.","false","Biography information for Justin Madders","Ellesmere Port and Neston","Justin Madders","50440"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622134","HM Treasury","false","2016-11-03","<p>Information on the original estimate for the savings can be found on p.35 of the ‘Autumn Statement 2013:policy costings’ document: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/263434/autumn_statement_2013_policy_costings.pdf" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/263434/autumn_statement_2013_policy_costings.pdf</a></p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison","50311","2016-11-03T15:27:46.8Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622134/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622134/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622134/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-10-26","Concentrix: Standards","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what target his Department set for savings to the public purse from the contract with Concentrix; and what the evidential basis for that target was.","false","Biography information for Justin Madders","Ellesmere Port and Neston","Justin Madders","50443"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622135","HM Treasury","false","2016-11-03","<p>The contract provides for a commission payment of an initial invoice value, with a subsequent quarterly reconciliation mechanism which takes into account supplier performance via specific Quality Performance Indicators and Key Performance indicators. These are linked to a defined service credit regime which includes accuracy of decisions.</p><p>Payment to Concentrix is reduced accordingly in line with the service credit regime should they fail to meet this target level of performance.</p><p>There is also an additional reconciliation process, again linked to the quality of reconsiderations made by Concentrix, which takes into wider account supplier performance and reduces commission payments if appropriate.</p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison","50313","2016-11-03T15:16:55.173Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622135/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622135/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622135/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-10-26","Concentrix","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, whether the Government plans to seek payment from Concentrix to fund any remedial action on erroneous decisions made by Concentrix against legitimate tax credit recipients.","false","Biography information for Justin Madders","Ellesmere Port and Neston","Justin Madders","50442"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622136","HM Treasury","false","2016-11-03","<p>HM Revenue and Customs has consistently and regularly reviewed Concentrix performance delivery with regard to all aspects of the contract. There are formal performance review mechanisms built into the contract, including weekly, monthly, quarterly and annual reviews.</p><p> </p><p>The contract has defined performance metrics, including Quality Performance Indicators, Key Performance Indicators and Standard Performance Indicators which are linked to an appropriate service credit regime (i.e. with payments being reduced if Concentrix fail to perform as required).</p><p> </p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison",,"2016-11-03T14:51:33.873Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622136/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622136/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622136/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-10-26","Concentrix: Standards","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, for what reasons (a) HM Revenue and Customs (HMRC) and (b) his Department have not investigated Concentrix's performance as required in Section 13.1 of the formal contract between HMRC and SYNNEX-Concentrix UK Limited.","false","Biography information for Justin Madders","Ellesmere Port and Neston","Justin Madders","50473"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622137","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-10-31","<p>As with all our policies, we aim to keep the payment by results model system under constant review to ensure that it continues to function effectively and fairly.</p><p> </p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds","50322","2016-10-31T16:53:24.67Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622137/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622137/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622137/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-10-26","Welfare State: Contracts","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, if he will conduct a review of all payment-by-results contracts in the welfare system; and if he will place a copy of the results of that review in the Library.","false","Biography information for Justin Madders","Ellesmere Port and Neston","Justin Madders","50474"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622138","HM Treasury","false","2016-11-03","<p>People with outstanding tax credit claims should contact HM Revenue and Customs (HMRC).</p><p> </p><p>The Concentrix contract is managed by the HMRC Commercial Team supported by HMRC Operational Service Management Team.</p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison","50481","2016-11-03T15:13:06.65Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622138/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622138/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622138/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-10-26","Concentrix","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, whether people with outstanding tax credit claims should contact Concentrix through their helpline or contact HM Revenue and Customs directly.","false","Biography information for Justin Madders","Ellesmere Port and Neston","Justin Madders","50475"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622139","Department of Health","false","2016-10-31","<p>The Spending Review settlement, delivered by the Chancellor on 25 November 2015, set the Department’s overall budget for the remaining years of the Parliament and the level of funding that will be available to the National Health Service. It set absolute spending totals providing certainty for financial planning over the period.</p><p> </p><p>The Department’s expenditure budgets are not adjusted for inflation but real terms growth in health expenditure is measured through Gross Domestic Product Deflators.</p><p> </p><p>Gross Domestic Deflators are produced by the Treasury from data provided by the Office for National Statistics. Forecasts are produced by the Office for Budgetary Responsibility and are usually updated around the time of major policy announcements, namely; the Chancellor’s Autumn Statement, and the Budget.</p>","Ludlow","Mr Philip Dunne",,"2016-10-31T17:38:59.49Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622139/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622139/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622139/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-10-26","NHS: Finance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, whether funding to the NHS will increase if inflation forecasts are revised upwards by the Office for Budget Responsibility.","false","Biography information for Justin Madders","Ellesmere Port and Neston","Justin Madders","50364"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622140","Department of Health","false","2016-10-31","<p>The Department publishes the payments it receives from companies who are members of the Pharmaceutical Price Regulation Scheme (PPRS) on the GOV.UK website at:</p><p> </p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/pprs-quarterly-net-sales-and-payment-information" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/pprs-quarterly-net-sales-and-payment-information</a></p><p> </p><p>Since the 2014 PPRS scheme began the Department has received £1,451 million in PPRS payments.</p><p> </p><p>The Department ensures that all the income it receives from PPRS payments in England is reinvested in the National Health Service for patients’ benefit. The Department includes the expected PPRS payments in setting the NHS England allocations in advance of each year.</p><p> </p><p>NHS England is responsible for allocating the overall budget between clinical commissioning groups, specialised commissioning etc. Following normal Government accounting rules, there is no separately identified or ring-fenced funding stream associated with the PPRS payment.</p>","Oxford West and Abingdon","Nicola Blackwood",,"2016-10-31T17:59:46.94Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622140/answer","Biography information for Baroness Blackwood of North Oxford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622140/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622140/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-10-26","Pharmaceutical Price Regulation Scheme","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, how much has been received to the public purse through the Pharmaceutical Price Regulation Scheme rebate since its inception; and for what purposes that funding has been used.","false","Biography information for Justin Madders","Ellesmere Port and Neston","Justin Madders","50330"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622141","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2016-11-02","<p>Ofgem check all of the information required to be provided by obligated energy companies for compliance against the legislation. This is supported by annual and risk-based audits.</p><p> </p><p>Ofgem also require the obligated energy companies to arrange for independent inspections to be conducted on at least 5% of installed measures, per energy company, to verify they have been installed in accordance with the relevant standards and that savings have been correctly calculated. From 1 April 2015 to date, 77,647 inspections have been conducted (41,172 of installation standards and 36,475 of savings) with a pass rate of 93.83%. Quarterly breakdowns of the number of inspections and outcomes are available in Ofgem’s published reports.</p><p> </p><p><a href="http://www.ofgem.gov.uk/environmental-programmes/eco/contacts-guidance-and-resources/eco-public-reports-and-data" target="_blank">www.ofgem.gov.uk/environmental-programmes/eco/contacts-guidance-and-resources/eco-public-reports-and-data</a></p><p> </p><p>Ofgem expects measures that failed this monitoring to be remediated and requires this to be reported to them by energy companies following a reinspection.</p><p> </p><p>Depending on the failure rate, Ofgem can require additional monitoring and assurances from companies that issues will not be replicated.</p><p><strong> </strong></p>","Hereford and South Herefordshire","Jesse Norman",,"2016-11-02T14:14:43.23Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622141/answer","Biography information for Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622141/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622141/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2016-10-26","Energy Companies Obligation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, pursuant to his Answer of 25 October 2016 to Question 49170, how many checks Ofgem has carried out to ensure that Energy Company Obligation scheme requirements have been met in each of the last 12 months for which figures are available.","false","Biography information for Justin Madders","Ellesmere Port and Neston","Justin Madders","50441"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622142","Department of Health","false","2016-10-31","<p>Clinical commissioning groups (CCGs) should take all possible steps to ensure that they are buying the best services for patients from the best providers available. It remains for commissioners to decide how best to procure services in the interests of their patients while seeking best value for taxpayers.</p><p> </p><p>In October 2016 the Department published guidance on the Public Contract Regulations 2015, which aims to support commissioners in complying with the Public Contract Regulations 2015.</p><p> </p><p>The guidance can be found at the following address:</p><p> </p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/public-contracts-regulations-2015-for-nhs-commissioners" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/public-contracts-regulations-2015-for-nhs-commissioners</a></p>","Ludlow","Mr Philip Dunne",,"2016-10-31T17:37:48.243Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622142/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622142/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622142/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-10-26","Health Services: Contracts","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, how his Department assesses the value for money of health service contracts that are tendered by clinical commissioning groups; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Clive Efford","Eltham","Clive Efford","50519"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622143","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-10-31","<p>Since autumn 2015 we have been working with 12 local authorities to develop evidence-based strategic delivery plans to embed relationship support into local services for families.</p><p>In light of the evidence review published by the Early Intervention Foundation, we are considering how best to build such capacity in all local areas, share information and support local strategic planning and delivery of services.</p><p>We also aim to launch soon an opportunity to bid for contracts to deliver targeted relationship support from 2017-18 onwards.</p><p> </p>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline Nokes",,"2016-10-31T16:44:06.553Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622143/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622143/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622143/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-10-26","Families","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what progress the Government has made on the Healthy Relationships Fund.","false","Biography information for Fiona Bruce","Congleton","Fiona Bruce","50529"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622144","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-10-31","<p>The Early Intervention Foundation review showed that children exposed to frequent, intense and poorly resolved conflict between their parents are at risk of poorer long term outcomes. Our new approach to relationship support responds to this evidence.</p><p>Since April 2016 we have doubled the funding available for relationship support for the remainder of this Parliament. From 2017/18 we will be contracting for relationship support services which will include both help targeted at the most disadvantaged families experiencing relationship distress, as well as universal support to help all families with information and advice on building better relationships.</p>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline Nokes",,"2016-10-31T16:28:21.707Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622144/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622144/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622144/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-10-26","Families: Government Assistance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, with reference to the Early Intervention Foundation review, What works to enhance interparental relationships and improve children's outcomes, commissioned by his Department and published on 22 March 2016, what steps he is taking to increase investment for interventions aimed at supporting parental relationships in order to improve children's mental health and life chances.","false","Biography information for Fiona Bruce","Congleton","Fiona Bruce","50590"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622145","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-10-31","<p>The report presented by the Early Intervention Foundation shows that children exposed to frequent, intense and poorly resolved conflict between their parents are at risk of poorer long term outcomes. Since publication policymakers have engaged with the Early Intervention Foundation through conferences and seminars to increase their understanding of the reports findings.</p><p>This evidence is being used to inform our approach to developing policy for future relationship support provision. Since autumn 2015 we have been working with 12 local authorities to develop evidence-based strategic delivery plans to embed relationship support into local services for families.</p><p>In addition we introduced the Family Test in October 2014, which means that for the first time new Government policies will be assessed for their impact on the family. This ensures that family stability is at the heart of government policy making.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline Nokes",,"2016-10-31T17:06:30.797Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622145/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622145/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622145/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-10-26","Families: Government Assistance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, with reference to the Early Intervention Foundation review, What works to enhance interparental relationships and improve children's outcomes, commissioned by his Department and published on 22 March 2016, what steps he is taking to strengthen the policymaker's role in promoting awareness of the effect of the quality of the relationship between parents on their children.","false","Biography information for Fiona Bruce","Congleton","Fiona Bruce","50589"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622146","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-10-31","<p>The Department has not made a formal assessment of the link between the quality of parental relationships on a child's life chances and the effectiveness of targeted relationship support. The report presented by the Early Intervention Foundation shows that children exposed to frequent, intense and poorly resolved conflict between their parents are at risk of poorer long term outcomes. This evidence is being used to inform our approach to developing policy for future relationship support provision.</p>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline Nokes",,"2016-10-31T16:18:34.417Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622146/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622146/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622146/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-10-26","Families: Government Assistance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, with reference to the Early Intervention Foundation review, What works to enhance interparental relationships and improve children's outcomes, commissioned by his Department and published on 22 March 2016, what assessment the Government has made of the (a) link between the quality of a parental relationship on a child's life chances and (b) effectiveness of targeted relationship support.","false","Biography information for Fiona Bruce","Congleton","Fiona Bruce","50588"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622147","HM Treasury","false","2016-10-31","<p>HM Revenue and Customs and Synnex-Concentrix UK Limited are currently in discussions to achieve a managed early exit from the contract. There are commercial sensitivities around the details at this time.</p><p> </p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison",,"2016-10-31T16:56:42.813Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622147/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622147/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622147/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-10-26","Concentrix: Standards","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, whether he plans to pay Synnex-Concentrix UK Limited any compensation as a result of the early termination of the HM Revenue and Customs Benefits and Credits, Errors and Fraud Adding Capacity 444 contract.","false","Biography information for Louise Haigh","Sheffield, Heeley","Louise Haigh","50596"
