"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622151","Department of Health","false","2016-11-03","<p>General practitioners (GPs) are independent contractors who hold contracts with NHS England to provide primary medical services for the National Health Service. Under the terms of their contract, GPs are required to provide certain medical reports or complete certain forms, such as those required to support a claim for incapacity benefit, free of charge to their registered patients.</p><p> </p><p>Outside of contractual requirements, GPs also provide a variety of other services which successive governments have regarded as private matters between the patient and the GP providing these services. In such cases, decisions on whether to charge a fee and the level of the fee charged are at the GP’s discretion. Where GPs intend to charge for services to patients, the British Medical Association advises them to forewarn patients, at the earliest opportunity, of the likely level of fees.</p>","Warrington South","David Mowat",,"2016-11-03T11:59:38.603Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622151/answer","Biography information for David Mowat","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622151/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622151/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-10-26","Medical Certificates: Fees and Charges","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, if he will take steps to ensure that GPs do not charge people with mental health conditions for the provision of a doctor's note.","false","Biography information for Helen Hayes","Dulwich and West Norwood","Helen Hayes","50361"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622152","HM Treasury","false","2016-11-02","<p>The Financial Conduct Authority (FCA) are currently undertaking a review of the regulatory regime for crowdfunding, including 36H of the Financial Services and Markets Act 2000 (Regulated Activities) (Amendment) (No.2) Order 2013. Possible changes to the regulatory regime will be considered in light of the findings of the FCA review.</p><p> </p><p>Further information on the review can be found on the FCA’s website at https://www.fca.org.uk/publications/calls-input/post-implementation-review-fca-crowdfunding-rules</p>","Brighton, Kemptown","Simon Kirby","50509","2016-11-02T15:39:25.497Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622152/answer","Biography information for Simon Kirby","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622152/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622152/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-10-26","Crowdfunding","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what plans he has to review the 36H regulations under the Financial Services and Markets Act 2000 (Regulated Activities) (Amendment) (No.2) Order 2013.","false","Biography information for Julian Knight","Solihull","Julian Knight","50614"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622153","HM Treasury","false","2016-11-02","<p>The Financial Conduct Authority (FCA) are currently undertaking a review of the regulatory regime for crowdfunding, including 36H of the Financial Services and Markets Act 2000 (Regulated Activities) (Amendment) (No.2) Order 2013. Possible changes to the regulatory regime will be considered in light of the findings of the FCA review.</p><p> </p><p>Further information on the review can be found on the FCA’s website at https://www.fca.org.uk/publications/calls-input/post-implementation-review-fca-crowdfunding-rules</p>","Brighton, Kemptown","Simon Kirby","50614","2016-11-02T15:39:25.56Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622153/answer","Biography information for Simon Kirby","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622153/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622153/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-10-26","Crowdfunding","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, if he will (a) review and (b) ease restrictions on intermediary balance sheet lending by platforms under 36H of the Financial Services and Markets Act 2000 (Regulated Activities) (Amendment) (No. 2) Order 2013.","false","Biography information for Julian Knight","Solihull","Julian Knight","50509"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622154","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-10-31","<p>As with all our policies, we aim to keep the payment by results model system under constant review to ensure that it continues to function effectively and fairly.</p><p> </p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds","50474","2016-10-31T16:53:24.607Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622154/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622154/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622154/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-10-26","Welfare State: Contracts","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, if he will conduct a review of all payment-by-results contracts in the welfare system; and if he will place a copy of the results of that review in the Library.","false","Biography information for Catherine West","Hornsey and Wood Green","Catherine West","50322"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622155","HM Treasury","false","2016-10-31","<p>HM Revenue and Customs (HMRC) is focused on resolving the outstanding cases. As at 30 October, of approximately 181,000 cases taken back by HMRC from Concentrix, around 178,000 are now finalised.</p><p> </p><p>As HMRC clears the work taken back from Concentrix, it will be working on a regional breakdown of mandatory reconsideration requests.</p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison","50324","2016-10-31T17:35:23.493Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622155/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622155/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622155/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-10-26","Concentrix: Haringey","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what estimate he has made of the number of tax credit cases awaiting consideration by Concentrix in (a) Hornsey and Wood Green constituency and (b) the London Borough of Haringey.","false","Biography information for Catherine West","Hornsey and Wood Green","Catherine West","50323"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622156","HM Treasury","false","2016-10-31","<p>HM Revenue and Customs (HMRC) is focused on resolving the outstanding cases. As at 30 October, of approximately 181,000 cases taken back by HMRC from Concentrix, around 178,000 are now finalised.</p><p> </p><p>As HMRC clears the work taken back from Concentrix, it will be working on a regional breakdown of mandatory reconsideration requests.</p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison","50323","2016-10-31T17:35:23.573Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622156/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622156/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622156/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-10-26","Concentrix: Haringey","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, how many people in (a) Hornsey and Wood Green constituency and (b) the London Borough of Haringey have had a tax credit claim stopped by Concentrix; and how many such claims were subsequently reinstated by HM Revenue and Customs.","false","Biography information for Catherine West","Hornsey and Wood Green","Catherine West","50324"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622157","HM Treasury","false","2016-10-31","<p>Concentrix is required to respond to any complaints which relate to the quality of their handling of compliance enquiries, as distinct from complaints on the substance of these investigations which are dealt with by HM Revenue and Customs (HMRC). HMRC will issue a response to each individual complaint received and, where appropriate, an apology if the standard of service is found lacking.</p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison",,"2016-10-31T16:55:31.907Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622157/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622157/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622157/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-10-26","Concentrix","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, whether (a) his Department, (b) HM Revenue and Customs and (c) Concentrix have issued a formal apology for each erroneous accusation made by Concentrix against legitimate tax credit recipients.","false","Biography information for Catherine West","Hornsey and Wood Green","Catherine West","50325"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622158","HM Treasury","false","2016-10-31","<p>HM Revenue and Customs has regularly reviewed Concentrix’s performance delivery with regard to all aspects of the contract.</p><p> </p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison",,"2016-10-31T16:57:21.213Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622158/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622158/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622158/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-10-26","Concentrix: Standards","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, with reference to section 13.1 of the formal contract between HM Revenue and Customs (HMRC) and SYNNEX-Concentrix Ltd, for what reasons (a) HMRC and (b) his Department has not investigated Concentrix's performance.","false","Biography information for Catherine West","Hornsey and Wood Green","Catherine West","50321"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622159","HM Treasury","false","2016-11-03","<p>Concentrix is a wholly-owned subsidiary of SYNNEX Corporation. HM Revenue and Customs (HMRC) is not responsible for, and does not hold information on, the number of staff Concentrix has employed in the UK in each year since 2014.</p><p> </p><p>As organisations conducting activities on behalf of HMRC and handling HMRC citizen information, Concentrix and each of its sub-contractors were made aware of their obligation of confidentiality under S18 of the Commissioners for Revenue and Customs Act 2005 and the Data Protection Act. This was done by the signing of corporate and individual non-disclosure agreements at the point of employment; face to face explanations of the requirements for security and confidentiality conducted in the first instance jointly by HMRC and Concentrix trainers. Later in the contract newly recruited employees were trained by Concentrix only trainers. Non-disclosure / confidentiality agreements were also put in place.</p><p> </p><p>All of the 181,000 cases taken back by HMRC from Concentrix are now finalised. HMRC is also continuing to work through all requests for Mandatory Reconsiderations of Concentrix decisions. Concentrix is no longer responsible for checking tax credit claims on behalf of HMRC.</p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison","50302 ; 50306 ; 50314","2016-11-03T17:31:09.617Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622159/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622159/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622159/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-10-26","Concentrix","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what estimate his Department has made of the backlog of tax credit cases which need to be dealt with by Concentrix and HM Revenue and Customs.","false","Biography information for Catherine West","Hornsey and Wood Green","Catherine West","50315"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622160","HM Treasury","false","2016-11-03","<p>Tax credits recipients are entitled to submit a request for Mandatory Reconsideration if a decision made by Concentrix is thought to be incorrect. Often, claimants are required to submit information that had originally been requested as part of a Mandatory Reconsideration.</p><p> </p><p>In addition, the performance of Concentrix is monitored by HM Revenue and Customs (HMRC). Any errors in tax credit awards checked by HMRC, including those where no Mandatory Reconsideration request has been submitted, are both reinstated and backdated, and so there are no savings to the Exchequer associated with these cases.</p><p> </p><p>HMRC does not have a comprehensive set of information on cases where no mandatory reconsideration has been submitted.</p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison","50476","2016-11-03T17:26:37.543Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622160/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622160/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622160/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-10-26","Concentrix","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what estimate his Department has made of tax credits savings to date which were as a result of erroneous accusations by Concentrix against legitimate tax credit recipients.","false","Biography information for Catherine West","Hornsey and Wood Green","Catherine West","50316"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622161","HM Treasury","false","2016-11-03","<p>HM Revenue and Customs receives a number of representations throughout the year on all aspects of tax credits. Representations increased significantly from mid-August onwards with regards to Concentrix.</p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison","50304","2016-11-03T17:40:03.937Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622161/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622161/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622161/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-10-26","Concentrix","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, on what date (a) HM Revenue and Customs and (b) his Department first received representations that Concentrix was erroneously investigating legitimate tax credit claimants and halting their payments.","false","Biography information for Catherine West","Hornsey and Wood Green","Catherine West","50305"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622162","HM Treasury","false","2016-11-03","<p>Concentrix is a wholly-owned subsidiary of SYNNEX Corporation. HM Revenue and Customs (HMRC) is not responsible for, and does not hold information on, the number of staff Concentrix has employed in the UK in each year since 2014.</p><p> </p><p>As organisations conducting activities on behalf of HMRC and handling HMRC citizen information, Concentrix and each of its sub-contractors were made aware of their obligation of confidentiality under S18 of the Commissioners for Revenue and Customs Act 2005 and the Data Protection Act. This was done by the signing of corporate and individual non-disclosure agreements at the point of employment; face to face explanations of the requirements for security and confidentiality conducted in the first instance jointly by HMRC and Concentrix trainers. Later in the contract newly recruited employees were trained by Concentrix only trainers. Non-disclosure / confidentiality agreements were also put in place.</p><p> </p><p>All of the 181,000 cases taken back by HMRC from Concentrix are now finalised. HMRC is also continuing to work through all requests for Mandatory Reconsiderations of Concentrix decisions. Concentrix is no longer responsible for checking tax credit claims on behalf of HMRC.</p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison","50302 ; 50314 ; 50315","2016-11-03T17:31:09.493Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622162/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622162/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622162/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-10-26","Revenue and Customs: Data Protection","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what support and guidance has been provided by his Department and HM Revenue and Customs to ensure that (a) Concentrix and (b) any body working on behalf of HM Revenue and Customs are aware of their obligations under the Data Protection Act.","false","Biography information for Catherine West","Hornsey and Wood Green","Catherine West","50306"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622163","HM Treasury","false","2016-11-03","<p>HM Revenue and Customs (HMRC) uses a wide range of mechanisms to monitor the performance of Concentrix. This includes active supplier management via dedicated commercial and operational teams and against defined targets, regular service delivery reviews and the collation of defined performance management information against targets.</p><p>As such, meetings (including telephone conferences) are conducted on a daily, weekly, monthly, quarterly and annual basis. HM Treasury also monitors the performance of Concentrix in conjunction with HMRC. Given these circumstances specific dates of meetings are not collated and published.</p><p>HMRC and HM Treasury do not routinely publish details of discussions with external suppliers.</p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison","50308 ; 50309 ; 50478 ; 50479 ; 50480","2016-11-03T17:38:03.027Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622163/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622163/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622163/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-10-26","Concentrix: Standards","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, if he will publish the minutes of meetings which were held between Concentrix and (a) HM Revenue and Customs and (b) his Department for the purposes of monitoring the performance of Concentrix.","false","Biography information for Catherine West","Hornsey and Wood Green","Catherine West","50307"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622164","HM Treasury","false","2016-11-03","<p>HM Revenue and Customs (HMRC) uses a wide range of mechanisms to monitor the performance of Concentrix. This includes active supplier management via dedicated commercial and operational teams and against defined targets, regular service delivery reviews and the collation of defined performance management information against targets.</p><p>As such, meetings (including telephone conferences) are conducted on a daily, weekly, monthly, quarterly and annual basis. HM Treasury also monitors the performance of Concentrix in conjunction with HMRC. Given these circumstances specific dates of meetings are not collated and published.</p><p>HMRC and HM Treasury do not routinely publish details of discussions with external suppliers.</p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison","50307 ; 50309 ; 50478 ; 50479 ; 50480","2016-11-03T17:38:03.12Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622164/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622164/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622164/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-10-26","Concentrix: Standards","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, if he will publish the dates of meetings which were held between Concentrix and (a) HM Revenue and Customs and (b) his Department for the purposes of monitoring the performance of Concentrix.","false","Biography information for Catherine West","Hornsey and Wood Green","Catherine West","50308"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622165","HM Treasury","false","2016-11-03","<p>HM Revenue and Customs (HMRC) uses a wide range of mechanisms to monitor the performance of Concentrix. This includes active supplier management via dedicated commercial and operational teams and against defined targets, regular service delivery reviews and the collation of defined performance management information against targets.</p><p>As such, meetings (including telephone conferences) are conducted on a daily, weekly, monthly, quarterly and annual basis. HM Treasury also monitors the performance of Concentrix in conjunction with HMRC. Given these circumstances specific dates of meetings are not collated and published.</p><p>HMRC and HM Treasury do not routinely publish details of discussions with external suppliers.</p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison","50307 ; 50308 ; 50478 ; 50479 ; 50480","2016-11-03T17:38:03.2Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622165/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622165/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622165/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-10-26","Concentrix: Standards","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, if he will publish performance reviews of the Concentrix tax credit contract conducted by (a) HM Revenue and Customs and (b) his Department.","false","Biography information for Catherine West","Hornsey and Wood Green","Catherine West","50309"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622166","HM Treasury","false","2016-11-03","<p>HM Revenue and Customs (HMRC) is urgently focusing on resolving the outstanding Concentrix cases.</p><p> </p><p>If people feel they have had their tax credits incorrectly withdrawn, they should urgently contact HMRC. HMRC will review all complaint cases and pay redress where appropriate. This will be carried out on a customer by customer basis.</p><p> </p><p>Any errors in tax credit awards checked by HMRC, including those where no Mandatory Reconsideration request has been submitted, are both reinstated and backdated.</p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison","50477","2016-11-03T14:49:16Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622166/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622166/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622166/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-10-26","Concentrix","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what timescale has been set for incorrect tax credit withdrawals by Concentrix to be remedied; and what plans he has to compensate claimants for any missing time periods.","false","Biography information for Catherine West","Hornsey and Wood Green","Catherine West","50310"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622167","HM Treasury","false","2016-11-03","<p>Information on the original estimate for the savings can be found on p.35 of the ‘Autumn Statement 2013:policy costings’ document: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/263434/autumn_statement_2013_policy_costings.pdf" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/263434/autumn_statement_2013_policy_costings.pdf</a></p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison","50443","2016-11-03T15:27:46.863Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622167/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622167/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622167/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-10-26","Concentrix: Standards","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what target his Department had for savings to the public purse from the Concentrix contract; and what the evidential basis for that target was.","false","Biography information for Catherine West","Hornsey and Wood Green","Catherine West","50311"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622168","HM Treasury","false","2016-11-03","<p>HM Revenue and Customs and Synnex-Concentrix UK Limited are in discussions to achieve a managed early exit from the contract. There are commercial sensitivities around the details at this time.</p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison","50440","2016-11-03T15:19:40.323Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622168/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622168/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622168/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-10-26","Concentrix","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, whether he plans to seek compensation from Concentrix to cover the cost of HM Revenue and Customs staff having to resolve tax credit claims (a) to date and (b) for the remaining duration of the contract with Concentrix.","false","Biography information for Catherine West","Hornsey and Wood Green","Catherine West","50312"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622169","HM Treasury","false","2016-11-03","<p>The contract provides for a commission payment of an initial invoice value, with a subsequent quarterly reconciliation mechanism which takes into account supplier performance via specific Quality Performance Indicators and Key Performance indicators. These are linked to a defined service credit regime which includes accuracy of decisions.</p><p>Payment to Concentrix is reduced accordingly in line with the service credit regime should they fail to meet this target level of performance.</p><p>There is also an additional reconciliation process, again linked to the quality of reconsiderations made by Concentrix, which takes into wider account supplier performance and reduces commission payments if appropriate.</p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison","50442","2016-11-03T15:16:55.253Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622169/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622169/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622169/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-10-26","Concentrix","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, whether the Government plans to seek payment from Concentrix to fund any remedial action on erroneous accusations made by Concentrix against legitimate tax credit recipients.","false","Biography information for Catherine West","Hornsey and Wood Green","Catherine West","50313"
