"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/620836","Attorney General","false","2016-10-28","<p>The Prime Minister will lead our negotiations for leaving the EU. This will be supported on a day-to-day basis by the Department for Exiting the European Union, which will work very closely with other government departments, including the Attorney General’s Office, and a wide range of other interested parties.</p>","South Swindon","Robert Buckland",,"2016-10-28T13:02:40.253Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/620836/answer","Biography information for Robert Buckland","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/620836/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/620836/answer",,,,,"88","Attorney General","Attorney General","2016-10-25","Attorney General: Brexit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Attorney General, what role he expects his Department to play in the negotiations on the UK leaving the EU.","false","Biography information for Mr Peter Bone","Wellingborough","Mr Peter Bone","50179"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/620837","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2016-10-28","<p>The Answer to Question 26796 included the table below setting out the average cost per participant since 2011.</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p><strong>Year</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Average cost per participant</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2011</p></td><td><p>£1,553</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2012</p></td><td><p>£1,700</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2013</p></td><td><p>£1,570</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2014</p></td><td><p>£1,538</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2015</p></td><td><p>Figures will be made available in the NCS 2015 evaluation report, which will be published in due course.</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p> </p><p>For each year, these costs are calculated by dividing the total cost of payments made from NCS Trust to NCS provider organisations by the total number of NCS participants. This approach was developed by independent experts.</p><p> </p><p>These figures do not include the operating costs of the NCS Trust. For further information on the NCS Trust’s operating budget, please see the published NCS Trust accounts which are available through Companies House.</p>","Reading East","Mr Rob Wilson",,"2016-10-28T13:44:59.02Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/620837/answer","Biography information for Mr Rob Wilson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/620837/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/620837/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2016-10-25","Voluntary Work: Young People","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, with reference to the Answer of 10 February 2016 to Question 26796, how the figure of (a) £1,500 allocated to each young person and (b) cost of running the NCS Trust was calculated.","false","Biography information for Stephen Doughty","Cardiff South and Penarth","Stephen Doughty","50176"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/620838","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2016-10-28","<p>The return on NCS is calculated on the basis of payments made to NCS provider organisations by the NCS Trust. The methodology for assessing the value for money of the NCS programme was developed by an independent evaluation expert.</p><p> </p>","Reading East","Mr Rob Wilson",,"2016-10-28T13:43:06.92Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/620838/answer","Biography information for Mr Rob Wilson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/620838/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/620838/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2016-10-25","National Citizen Service Trust","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, pursuant to the Answer of 10 February 2016 to Question 26796, whether the return of £3.98 for every £1 spent on the National Citizen Service is calculated on the basis of the cost of (a) delivery and (b) running the National Citizen Service Trust.","false","Biography information for Stephen Doughty","Cardiff South and Penarth","Stephen Doughty","50181"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/620839","Cabinet Office","false","2016-10-28","<p>We have held three roundtable discussions with employers and stakeholders to develop new measures of socio-economic background. Matt Hancock, the then Minister for the Cabinet Office and Paymaster General, in March of this year hosted the first roundtable, which formed the basis for co-creation of the online open consultation on 26 potential measures of Socio-Economic Background. During the consultation which ran from 26 May to 24 June, two further events were held on 15 and 17 June, which were led by officials.</p>","Kingswood","Chris Skidmore",,"2016-10-28T07:18:21Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/620839/answer","Biography information for Chris Skidmore","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/620839/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/620839/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2016-10-25","Social Class","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, how many regional roundtables with employers his Department has held to develop new measures of socio-economic background.","false","Biography information for Andrew Gwynne","Denton and Reddish","Andrew Gwynne","50205"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/620840","Cabinet Office","false","2016-11-01","<p>As set out in the Cabinet Manual, departmental civil servants provide advice to ministers on the extent of their powers. There are no plans to issue guidance from the Cabinet Office.</p>","Kingswood","Chris Skidmore",,"2016-11-01T08:55:57.247Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/620840/answer","Biography information for Chris Skidmore","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/620840/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/620840/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2016-10-25","Royal Prerogative","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, if he will provide guidance to Government departments on the Government's current definition of the prerogative power.","false","Biography information for Paul Flynn","Newport West","Paul Flynn","50060"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/620841","Cabinet Office","false","2016-10-31","<p>Copycat websites undermine trust in online services, and this government is committed to stopping them. We’re taking action on three fronts.</p><p>First, we are taking action to shut down such sites and prevent them from appearing in search engines. We are working with search engine providers to ensure they implement their terms and conditions on copycat website advertising, increasing the click-through to Government websites by 30%. Security teams in departments across government are also actively monitoring the internet for bogus sites, and taking action accordingly.</p><p>Secondly we improve the consistency and quality of Government websites, so that consumers can recognise and trust official sources of information.</p><p>Finally, we are working closely with other bodies such as the Advertising Standards Authority (ASA), the National Trading Standards Board (NTSB) and Which? to raise awareness of this issue and ensure action is taken where appropriate.</p>","Kingswood","Chris Skidmore",,"2016-10-31T10:12:19.327Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/620841/answer","Biography information for Chris Skidmore","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/620841/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/620841/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2016-10-25","Electronic Government","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, what steps the Government is taking to monitor copycat websites that offer government services.","false","Biography information for Craig Whittaker","Calder Valley","Craig Whittaker","50062"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/620842","HM Treasury","false","2016-11-02","<p>The government considers that the National Infrastructure Commission will have the right tools to deliver its objectives and operate effectively as an executive agency.</p><p> </p><p>It will continue to provide robust, impartial analysis and advice on the country’s most complex and pressing infrastructure challenges. Setting up the NIC as an executive agency will mean that the Commission can be up and running in permanent form as soon as January 2017.</p><p> </p>","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke",,"2016-11-02T16:43:13.827Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/620842/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/620842/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/620842/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-10-25","National Infrastructure Commission","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, for what reasons the National Infrastructure Commission is to be established as an executive agency rather than as a non-departmental public body.","false","Biography information for Stephen Kinnock","Aberavon","Stephen Kinnock","50070"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/620843","HM Treasury","false","2016-11-02","<p>There will be no cash losers as a result of the Government’s policy to limit support to two children in Child Tax Credit and Universal Credit. An impact assessment of Tax Credits and Universal Credit changes to Child Element and Family Element was published in July 2015.</p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison",,"2016-11-02T11:53:36.007Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/620843/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/620843/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/620843/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-10-25","Child Tax Credit","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, if his Department will carry out an impact assessment on the effect on child poverty levels of limiting tax credit payments to two children.","false","Biography information for Alison Thewliss","Glasgow Central","Alison Thewliss","50046"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/620844","HM Treasury","false","2016-11-02","<p>HM Revenue and Customs staff being relocated to the Croydon Regional Centre are in the process of one to one meetings with managers to discuss personal circumstances and establish whether or not they can move. The discussions undertaken to date indicate that the majority of people are within reasonable daily travel of the new regional centre.</p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison",,"2016-11-02T16:16:53.82Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/620844/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/620844/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/620844/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-10-25","Revenue and Customs: Croydon","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what proportion of staff being relocated to Croydon regional centre by HM Revenue and Customs have been deemed as living within reasonable daily travel of the centre; and what the basis was for that assessment.","false","Biography information for Stuart C. McDonald","Cumbernauld, Kilsyth and Kirkintilloch East","Stuart C. McDonald","50101"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/620845","HM Treasury","false","2016-11-02","<p>The table below shows all dismissals from 1 April 2006 and the number of people dismissed who have recorded their disability status as disabled and non-disabled.</p><table><tbody><tr><td><p><strong>Year</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Total No. Of Dismissals</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Recorded Disabled status</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Not Recorded Disabled status</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2006/07</p></td><td><p>150</p></td><td><p>0</p></td><td><p>150</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2007/08</p></td><td><p>386</p></td><td><p>10</p></td><td><p>376</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2008/09</p></td><td><p>457</p></td><td><p>33</p></td><td><p>424</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2009/10</p></td><td><p>530</p></td><td><p>74</p></td><td><p>456</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2010/11</p></td><td><p>467</p></td><td><p>94</p></td><td><p>373</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2011/12</p></td><td><p>511</p></td><td><p>84</p></td><td><p>427</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2012/13</p></td><td><p>510</p></td><td><p>100</p></td><td><p>410</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2013/14</p></td><td><p>449</p></td><td><p>83</p></td><td><p>366</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2014/15</p></td><td><p>346</p></td><td><p>63</p></td><td><p>283</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2015/16</p></td><td><p>522</p></td><td><p>88</p></td><td><p>434</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2016/17</p></td><td><p>235</p></td><td><p>37</p></td><td><p>198</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>All Years Total</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>4,563</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>666</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>1,242</strong></p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p>HM Revenue and Customs runs regular educational campaigns to encourage people to declare their disability status. For the Department as a whole, the disability declaration rate has increased from 5.4% in 2006 to 60.4% in 2016. As at 30 September 2016, 14.82% of the Department have recorded themselves as disabled.</p><p> </p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison",,"2016-11-02T17:13:35.217Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/620845/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/620845/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/620845/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-10-25","Revenue and Customs: Dismissal","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, how many HM Revenue and Customs' staff have been dismissed in each year since 2006; and what proportion of those staff were disabled.","false","Biography information for Stuart C. McDonald","Cumbernauld, Kilsyth and Kirkintilloch East","Stuart C. McDonald","50102"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/620846","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2016-11-02","<p>We will consider the findings of the independent review of tidal lagoons, which is due to report by the end of 2016, before deciding how to proceed.</p>","Hereford and South Herefordshire","Jesse Norman",,"2016-11-02T12:31:28.177Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/620846/answer","Biography information for Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/620846/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/620846/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2016-10-25","Tidal Power: Swansea Bay","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, when he plans to announce a decision on the Swansea Bay Tidal Lagoon.","false","Biography information for Stephen Kinnock","Aberavon","Stephen Kinnock","50103"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/620847","HM Treasury","false","2016-11-02","<p>HM Revenue and Customs’ (HMRC) transformation programme will deliver 13 large regional centres, four specialist sites, one London-based headquarters and five transitional locations across the country, replacing 170 smaller offices. The planning for this major programme is undertaken at national level and HMRC’s decision making has been driven by its duty to deliver the best value for money for the taxpayer. Its location plans are expected to generate savings of tens of millions of pounds every year from 2025.</p><p>The HMRC office in Cumbernauld is scheduled to close in 2019-20. HMRC believes that the majority of staff are within reasonable daily travel of Glasgow and will move with their work.</p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison","50140 ; 50269","2016-11-02T15:58:44.44Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/620847/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/620847/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/620847/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-10-25","Revenue and Customs: Cumbernauld","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what plans are in place to mitigate the potential economic effect of the proposal to close HM Revenue and Custom's Cumbernauld tax office.","false","Biography information for Stuart C. McDonald","Cumbernauld, Kilsyth and Kirkintilloch East","Stuart C. McDonald","50139"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/620848","HM Treasury","false","2016-11-02","<p>HM Revenue and Customs’ (HMRC) transformation programme will deliver 13 large regional centres, four specialist sites, one London-based headquarters and five transitional locations across the country, replacing 170 smaller offices. The planning for this major programme is undertaken at national level and HMRC’s decision making has been driven by its duty to deliver the best value for money for the taxpayer. Its location plans are expected to generate savings of tens of millions of pounds every year from 2025.</p><p>The HMRC office in Cumbernauld is scheduled to close in 2019-20. HMRC believes that the majority of staff are within reasonable daily travel of Glasgow and will move with their work.</p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison","50139 ; 50269","2016-11-02T15:58:44.517Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/620848/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/620848/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/620848/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-10-25","Revenue and Customs: Cumbernauld","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, if he will publish the detailed estimate his Department has made of the potential costs and savings of the proposed relocation of staff from Cumbernauld tax office to a new site in Glasgow.","false","Biography information for Stuart C. McDonald","Cumbernauld, Kilsyth and Kirkintilloch East","Stuart C. McDonald","50140"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/620849","HM Treasury","false","2016-10-28","<p>The Local Majors Fund supports local transport scheme bids which are too big to receive support from the Local Growth Fund. At the Spending Review in 2015, the Government announced the Local Majors Fund would comprise £475 million of funding over this Parliament. This Fund forms part of the Government’s commitment to infrastructure – over 3000 infrastructure projects have been delivered across the country since 2010.</p><p> </p>","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke",,"2016-10-28T10:43:23.823Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/620849/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/620849/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/620849/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-10-25","Roads: Capital Investment","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, if he will increase the Local Majors Fund.","false","Biography information for Mims Davies","Eastleigh","Mims Davies","50185"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/620850","HM Treasury","false","2016-10-28","<p>An assessment of the impact of the verification scheme was published in 2012 as part of a consultation: <a href="http://webarchive.nationalarchives.gov.uk/20121205004423/http:/customs.hmrc.gov.uk/channelsPortalWebApp/channelsPortalWebApp.portal?_nfpb=true&amp;_pageLabel=pageLibrary_ConsultationDocuments&amp;propertyType=document&amp;columns=1&amp;id=HMCE_PROD1_032348" target="_blank">http://webarchive.nationalarchives.gov.uk/20121205004423/http://customs.hmrc.gov.uk/channelsPortalWebApp/channelsPortalWebApp.portal?_nfpb=true&amp;_pageLabel=pageLibrary_ConsultationDocuments&amp;propertyType=document&amp;columns=1&amp;id=HMCE_PROD1_032348</a></p><p> </p><p>No respondents to the consultation suggested an alternative method of apportioning the costs of the scheme; this was reflected in a subsequent assessment of impacts, although this has not been published.</p><p> </p><p>The Spirit Drinks (Costs of Verification) Regulations 2013 require the Commissioners for HM Revenue and Customs to review the operation and effect of these regulations and publish a report within five years of them coming into effect. Such a report will be produced in 2018.</p><p> </p><p>There have been no reports to say that the standard charge is a barrier to entry for small and new entrant producers or a barrier to trade. The Government would welcome any evidence that the fees are a barrier to entry.</p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison",,"2016-10-28T10:41:16.467Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/620850/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/620850/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/620850/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-10-25","Excise Duties: Spirits","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what assessment he has made of the economic effect on small and new-entrant producers of the introduction of the standard charge imposed by HM Revenue and Customs under the Spirit Drinks Verification Scheme; and what reports he has received of whether the standard charge is a barrier to entry for small and new-entrant producers and a restraint on trade.","false","Biography information for Angus Brendan MacNeil","Na h-Eileanan an Iar","Angus Brendan MacNeil","50189"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/620851","HM Treasury","false","2016-11-02","<p>HM Revenue and Customs’ (HMRC) transformation programme will deliver 13 large regional centres, four specialist sites, one London-based headquarters and five transitional locations across the country, replacing 170 smaller offices. The planning for this major programme is undertaken at national level and HMRC’s decision making has been driven by its duty to deliver the best value for money for the taxpayer. Its location plans are expected to generate savings of tens of millions of pounds every year from 2025.</p><p>The HMRC office in Cumbernauld is scheduled to close in 2019-20. HMRC believes that the majority of staff are within reasonable daily travel of Glasgow and will move with their work.</p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison","50139 ; 50140","2016-11-02T15:58:44.58Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/620851/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/620851/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/620851/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-10-25","Revenue and Customs: Cumbernauld","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, with reference to the Answer of 26 October 2015 to Question 12759, if he will publish assessments made by HM Revenue and Customs of the local economic issues, business requirements, impact on current workforce and location principles in relation to the decision to close Cumbernauld tax office.","false","Biography information for Stuart C. McDonald","Cumbernauld, Kilsyth and Kirkintilloch East","Stuart C. McDonald","50269"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/620852","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-02-01","<p>As confirmed to the House on 23 January 2017, Official Report, column 69, devolving Attendance Allowance funding is no longer being considered as a part of the current business rates retention reforms.</p>","Nuneaton","Mr Marcus Jones","50216","2017-02-01T15:01:39.223Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/620852/answer","Biography information for Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/620852/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/620852/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2016-10-25","Attendance Allowance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what assessment he has made of the effect of devolution of attendance allowance to local authorities on the future expenditure on that benefit; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Mr Jim Cunningham","Coventry South","Mr Jim Cunningham","50282"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/620853","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-02-01","<p>As confirmed to the House on 23 January 2017, Official Report, column 69, devolving Attendance Allowance funding is no longer being considered as a part of the current business rates retention reforms.</p>","Nuneaton","Mr Marcus Jones","50282","2017-02-01T15:01:39.27Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/620853/answer","Biography information for Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/620853/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/620853/answer","Nuneaton","Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/620853/answer/previousversion/17194","Biography information for Mr Marcus Jones","7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2016-10-25","Attendance Allowance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what assessment he has made of the potential effect of the devolution of attendance allowance to local authorities on future regional variations in that allowance; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Mr Jim Cunningham","Coventry South","Mr Jim Cunningham","50216"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/620854","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2016-11-02","<p>Council Tax is a locally raised and set, and it is for local authorities to decide whether they wish to make use of the adult social care ‘precept’. The government has published figures for Core Spending Power each area and each year up to 2019-20, which includes the amount of funding that would be available to them if they chose to take advantage of it.</p>","Nuneaton","Mr Marcus Jones",,"2016-11-02T16:39:38.85Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/620854/answer","Biography information for Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/620854/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/620854/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2016-10-25","Social Services: Council Tax","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what estimate he has made of the potential uptake of social care precept by councils in each year to 2020-21.","false","Biography information for Helen Hayes","Dulwich and West Norwood","Helen Hayes","50100"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/620855","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2016-11-02","<p>The Government does not collect data regarding the effect of online retailers on small high street businesses. The growing ‘convenience culture’, with 35% of online shoppers using click and collect, is boosting the traditional high streets revival, driving people back on to the high street. <br> <br> This Government has also taken action<strong>:</strong> our high streets will benefit from the £6 billion Business Rates support package announced at the last Budget. Since 2010, the Government has helped create over 360 town teams, and given over £18 million to towns - funding successful initiatives such as “Love your Local Market” and the “Great British High Street”. <br> <br> The Future High Street Forum commissioned a Digital report, Digital 2020, which was published in March 2015 which looked at what help our high street businesses need to adapt in the digital age. A digital pilot in Gloucestershire was launched earlier this year with the support of the Future High Street Forum and GFirst LEP to support SMEs to embrace digital.</p>","Brigg and Goole","Andrew Percy",,"2016-11-02T16:39:14.163Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/620855/answer","Biography information for Andrew Percy","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/620855/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/620855/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2016-10-25","Home Shopping","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what assessment his Department has made of the effect of online retailers on small high street businesses.","false","Biography information for Andrew Gwynne","Denton and Reddish","Andrew Gwynne","50088"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/620856","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2016-10-28","<p>The Department has not issued guidance to social landlords including local authorities, regarding managing tenancy agreements of victims of domestic violence who are joint tenants when the abusive partner moves out.</p><p>Local authorities have powers to take action against joint tenants who commit domestic abuse against their partners including a power under the Housing Act 1985 to apply to the court to evict such perpetrators and have the discretion to grant a new tenancy to the victim.</p><p>Many local authorities use these powers as part of their proactive approach towards assisting tenants affected by domestic abuse to remain in their homes safely if they choose to do so.</p><p>Domestic abuse is a devastating crime, and Government has put in place a number of measures to provide necessary support to victims.</p><p>Our Violence Against Women and Girls Strategy, launched earlier this year, set out our ambition to improve services for women suffering from domestic abuse, dedicating £40 million of extra funding for securing the future of refuges and other specialist accommodation-based services. This builds on the £13.5 million provided in the last spending review period. In addition, we will be providing a wider package of support, including commissioning guidance and tools, and expert support to help all local areas improve local commissioning, support early intervention and develop coherent pathways of support for victims of these crimes. This provides a critical bedrock of support.</p><p>In taking forward the provisions in the Housing and Planning Act 2016 that restrict the use of lifetime tenancies, we will also ensure that the security of tenure of victims of domestic abuse continues to be protected.</p>","Croydon Central","Gavin Barwell",,"2016-10-28T13:36:37.373Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/620856/answer","Biography information for Lord Barwell","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/620856/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/620856/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2016-10-25","Tenancy Agreements: Domestic Abuse","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what guidance his Department issues to social landlords on transfer of tenancy agreements to victims of domestic violence when that person's relationship with their abusive partner ends and the victim remains the sole adult tenant after the ex-partner moves out.","false","Biography information for Thangam Debbonaire","Bristol West","Thangam Debbonaire","50080"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/620857","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2016-11-01","<p>All local authorities are required by law to set a balanced budget each year, and to appoint an officer who has responsibility to report on the reasonableness of assumptions underpinning each budget. Local authority functions are set out in numerous Acts of Parliament and many of these functions have associated legal duties. Local authorities are democratically elected organisations, and as such are responsible for decisions on how to achieve value for money in line with local circumstances and priorities.</p>","Nuneaton","Mr Marcus Jones",,"2016-11-01T15:34:40.577Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/620857/answer","Biography information for Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/620857/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/620857/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2016-10-25","Local Government Finance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what guidance his Department issues to local authorities on budget setting processes to ensure (a) value for money for residents and (b) the delivery of core frontline services.","false","Biography information for Craig Whittaker","Calder Valley","Craig Whittaker","50063"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/620858","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2016-10-28","<p>The Advertising Standards Authority (ASA) is responsible for the regulation of advertising. The ASA’s rule-making arm is the Committee of Advertising Practice (CAP). The ASA is an independent regulator and a limited company funded by industry. It operates a self-regulatory regime for non-broadcast advertising and has a co-regulatory relationship with Ofcom for broadcast advertising.</p>","West Suffolk","Matt Hancock",,"2016-10-28T10:47:47.113Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/620858/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/620858/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/620858/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2016-10-25","Advertising: Regulation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, pursuant to the Answer of 24 October 2016 to Question 49394, on communication: competition, whether Ofcom has responsibility relating to the regulation of the advertising sector in relation to communications markets.","false","Biography information for Chi Onwurah","Newcastle upon Tyne Central","Chi Onwurah","50077"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/620859","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2016-11-04","<p>Funding decisions are a matter for the Arts Council England. The Government has been clear that the right balance of funding between London and the regions continues to require attention as part of our commitment to build a country that works for everyone. It is important that regardless of location, everyone should be able to access great arts and culture. Arts Council England continue to work on this and recently announced that the proportion of the national portfolio budget spent outside London will increase from 2018.</p><p> </p><p>Spending in individual regions fluctuates from year to year and is heavily affected by individual large scale capital funding projects. However as the attached table shows, 2015-16 saw the largest proportion of spending outside London than in any of the previous 10 years – including five years of a Labour government.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","West Suffolk","Matt Hancock",,"2016-11-04T10:19:39.53Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/620859/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/620859/answer","PQ 50091- Spend per head by region 2005-16 26.10.16 (1).xlsx","Spend per head by region 2005-16","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/620859/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2016-10-25","Arts: Expenditure","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, what the level of arts spending per head in each of the regions of England has been in each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for Tom Blenkinsop","Middlesbrough South and East Cleveland","Tom Blenkinsop","50091"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/620860","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2016-10-28","<p>This information will be deposited in the Parliamentary Libraries in due course.</p><p> </p>","Reading East","Mr Rob Wilson",,"2016-10-28T13:39:30.59Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/620860/answer","Biography information for Mr Rob Wilson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/620860/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/620860/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2016-10-25","Voluntary Work: Children","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, how many people have participated in the National Citizen Service from each local authority area in each year since that service was introduced.","false","Biography information for Mr Steve Reed","Croydon North","Mr Steve Reed","50092"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/620861","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2016-10-28","<p>Ever since the programme’s inception, young people from lower socio-economic backgrounds in receipt of free school meals have been well represented. For example, in 2014, 17% of NCS participants were eligible for free school meals, compared with around 8% of young people of the same age in the general population.</p><p>All data collected on the backgrounds of NCS participants is self-declared.</p><table><tbody><tr><td><p><strong>Year</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>No. of NCS participants eligible for free school meals</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Percentage of total participants</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2011</p></td><td><p>1,940</p></td><td><p>23%</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2012</p></td><td><p>5,460</p></td><td><p>21%</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2013</p></td><td><p>7,300</p></td><td><p>16%</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2014</p></td><td><p>9,280</p></td><td><p>17%</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p>The results of the independent 2015 evaluation will be published in due course.</p>","Reading East","Mr Rob Wilson",,"2016-10-28T13:41:16.857Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/620861/answer","Biography information for Mr Rob Wilson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/620861/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/620861/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2016-10-25","Voluntary Work: Children","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, how many participants in the National Citizen Service have been eligible for free school meals in each year since that service was introduced.","false","Biography information for Mr Steve Reed","Croydon North","Mr Steve Reed","50093"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/620862","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2016-10-28","<p>The Government has not directly invested in the Gaelic Athletic Association.</p><p>Since 2010, Sport England has invested £961,414 in 24 multi-sports projects which include Gaelic sport.</p><p> </p><p>Sport England has received an application from the British Gaelic Athletic Association to be the recognised NGB for Gaelic sports in Britain, and has met the representatives from the British Gaelic Athletic Association to offer help and advice on its application.</p>","Chatham and Aylesford","Tracey Crouch",,"2016-10-28T11:11:07.53Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/620862/answer","Biography information for Tracey Crouch","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/620862/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/620862/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2016-10-25","Gaelic Athletic Association","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, what (a) financial and (b) other support her Department has provided for Gaelic Athletic Association activities in England.","false","Biography information for Conor McGinn","St Helens North","Conor McGinn","50094"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/620863","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2016-10-28","<p>Following cross-party talks on the recommendations in Silk II there was (a) consensus to reject plans to devolve responsibility for funding public expenditure element of S4C to Assembly and (b) consensus to agree that the regulation of broadcasting should remain responsibility of the UK Government.</p>","West Suffolk","Matt Hancock",,"2016-10-28T11:06:06.333Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/620863/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/620863/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/620863/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2016-10-25","Broadcasting: Wales","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, what her policy is on devolving responsibility for (a) S4C and (b) all aspects of broadcasting to the National Assembly for Wales.","false","Biography information for Jonathan Edwards","Carmarthen East and Dinefwr","Jonathan Edwards","50131"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/620864","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2016-10-31","<p>We strongly support S4C. We work closely and collaboratively with the Welsh Government on areas of common interest - including the proposed review of S4C.</p>","West Suffolk","Matt Hancock",,"2016-10-31T10:34:08.26Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/620864/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/620864/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/620864/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2016-10-25","S4C Independent Review","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, what discussions she has had with the Welsh Office on the Government's review of S4C.","false","Biography information for Hywel Williams","Arfon","Hywel Williams","50290"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/620865","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2016-10-31","<p>The Government is committed to a comprehensive review of S4C in 2017 covering remit, funding and governance. Further details including the name of the reviewer, terms of reference and process will be announced in due course.</p>","West Suffolk","Matt Hancock","50292","2016-10-31T10:32:52.393Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/620865/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/620865/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/620865/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2016-10-25","S4C Independent Review","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, how she plans to ensure that the review of S4C is independent.","false","Biography information for Hywel Williams","Arfon","Hywel Williams","50291"
